reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network uses literature-grounded prebiotic routes that converge on L-proline through the best-supported precursor logic: hydrothermal H2-driven formation of alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate, followed by nonenzymatic reduction/cyclization through glutamate semialdehyde and Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate, plus direct low-yield mixed-chemistry production in lightning/discharge and UV-rich surface settings. Surface environments also supply HCN-derived nitrogen chemistry, concentration, phosphorylation/condensation context, and mineral adsorption that preserves intermediates and enables downstream biochemical assembly. Because the literature shows no dedicated high-yield proline synthesis, several reactions are explicitly marked as speculative-but-necessary connectors consistent with the reported alphaKG -> glutamate -> glutamate-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline framework.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetic acid/acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide oxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butan-1-amine with aminomethyl substitution\",\n      \"common_name\": \"butylamine precursor pool\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is central to alkaline vent chemistry and is consistent with the hydrothermal framework given here. This step provides a carbon-reduced feedstock for downstream ketoacid formation and cross-environment transfer. Supported by hydrothermal Fe-S carbon fixation concepts and vent chemistry summarized in Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997 and Somorjai et al., 2023.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate homologation to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent interface, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S surfaces generate acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate generation from reduced C1 species under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis matches the acetyl-CoA analog logic discussed for vent chemistry and supplies a C2 node for pyruvate and alpha-ketoglutarate emergence. Supported by Fe-S carbon fixation concepts in Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997 and contextualized in Somorjai et al., 2023.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface reduction of CO2/CO-derived intermediates followed by C-C coupling yields small aldehydes including glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite and reduced iron is a plausible source of aldehydes used later in surface sugar and nitrile chemistry. This is used here as a connector to literature-supported HCN-rich and mixed-chemistry contexts. Supported generally by hydrothermal carbonyl synthesis literature and integrated prebiotic network logic in Kaur et al., 2024 and Somorjai et al., 2023.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive C1/C2 assimilation and mineral-mediated carboxylation/condensation generate alpha-keto acid functionality, producing pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a central hydrothermal hub in protometabolic analogs and is a required precursor to larger alpha-keto acids. This reaction is a network-level connector consistent with H2-driven prebiotic carbon fixation and ketoacid generation. Supported by prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog chemistry in Kaur et al., 2024 and vent-based carbon fixation rationale in Somorjai et al., 2023.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal and meteoritic analog alpha-ketoglutarate formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing mineral surface associated with pyrite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, H2-accessible, meteorite-powder or Ni-rich mineral analog context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive aldol-like network expansion from smaller carbonyls and ketoacids gives larger alpha-keto acids including alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) experimentally demonstrated an H2/NH4+-driven prebiotic Krebs cycle analog over Ni or meteorite powder at 22C and pH 8 producing biological ketoacids and amino acids including glutamate from alphaKG. This network therefore includes alphaKG as a justified hydrothermal-to-mild aqueous hub, though exact stepwise assembly from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde is a necessary connector rather than directly isolated. Supported by Kaur et al., 2024.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing mineral surface on Fe-S background\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, NH4Cl 6-150 mM equivalent ammonium, H2 atmosphere, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between alpha-keto acid and ammonia/ammonium followed by H2-driven reduction on metal-rich mineral surfaces gives glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is one of the strongest literature-supported steps relevant to proline: Kaur et al. (2024) showed alpha-keto acids including alpha-ketoglutarate are aminated to corresponding amino acids under H2, NH4+, and Ni or meteorite powder at 22C, pH 8. This directly supplies glutamate, the canonical biochemical precursor to proline. Supported by Kaur et al., 2024.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing Fe-S-rich microenvironment, moderate pH, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of the gamma-carboxyl group of glutamate furnishes the corresponding semialdehyde without altering the alpha-amino acid center.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Somorjai et al. (2023) explicitly discuss the prebiotic plausibility of the biological sequence glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline as a nonenzymatic route. The exact mineral/chemical reductant is not experimentally fixed in the report, so this step is included as a literature-motivated but still speculative bottleneck consistent with Fe-S/H2 reducing environments. Supported by Somorjai et al., 2023; challenge acknowledged in the deep research summary.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intramolecular cyclization in concentrated prebiotic pools or interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amino aldehyde undergoes intramolecular condensation to a five-membered cyclic imine/carboxylate system, producing Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C is the core chemical logic linking glutamate to proline in both biology and the prebiotic framework described in the research summary. Supported conceptually by Somorjai et al., 2023 and the precursor discussion in the deep research findings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing prebiotic pool or mineral interface, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogenation/reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C yields proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final reduction closes the canonical glutamate-derived route to proline. The deep research report identifies P5C reduction as the last step and notes available reductants such as H2/metal as plausible. The exact prebiotic selectivity for L-proline remains unresolved, so stereochemical enrichment is speculative. Supported by Somorjai et al., 2023; challenge noted in Ring et al., 1972 and the report's discussion of low yields and racemic outcomes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface lightning/discharge synthesis of HCN-rich precursor pool and trace proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"approximately 298K bulk flask with local plasma heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge with mineral collection surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CH4-N2-H2O-NH3 spark-discharge analog; no O2; strong high-energy input\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Plasma-generated radicals from reduced C/N gases form cyanides, nitriles, and complex radical intermediates that hydrolyze/recombine into amino acids including trace proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ring et al. (1972) reported proline among amino acids formed in Miller-Urey-type CH4/N2/H2O/NH3 spark experiments. The specific mechanism for proline is unresolved, but mixed radical chemistry is the only direct experimental evidence for abiotic proline formation. Mineral agents are included here to satisfy the surface-network requirement as collection/photocatalytic surfaces rather than the primary energetic driver. Supported by Ring et al., 1972.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV nitrile chemistry from HCN to formamide and amine-rich precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"200-300K in ice analogs to 300-350K on surfaces\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm or low-pressure ice analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"nitrile-rich, anoxic, strong UV; icy or evaporitic concentration settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-rich photochemistry generates formamide and more complex amine/nitrile species through radical addition, hydration, and oligomer-fragmentation chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies HCN polymerization/cyanosulfidic chemistry as a plausible source of amino-imines and aminonitriles and notes UV irradiation of simple ices can yield proline-related chemistry. Formamide is a standard HCN photoproduct, while butylamine-like amine precursors are specifically discussed in UV-ice work as stepping stones toward proline. This reaction is therefore a literature-aligned precursor-pool node rather than a single defined transformation. Supported by Simionato et al., 2018.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-ice radical route from butylamine-like precursor pool to trace proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<100K in ice analog experiments, then warming to recovery\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photolysis with mineral trapping surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"interstellar/cometary ice analog or cold surface ice, radical-radical chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-induced radical formation and recombination in amine-containing ices yields cyclic amino acid products including proline upon warm-up/hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. (2018) summarize astrochemical ice experiments in which UV photolysis of simple ices yields proline and discuss butylamine as a plausible precursor in radical-radical mechanisms. This is included as a direct but low-yield alternative route to proline entering the surface inventory. Supported by Simionato et al., 2018.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal glutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent carbon fixation produces alpha-ketoglutarate, which undergoes H2/NH3 reductive amination to glutamate followed by semialdehyde formation, cyclization, and reduction to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde-assisted protometabolic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde formation feeds a protometabolic expansion to alpha-ketoglutarate, then follows the glutamate/P5C route to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-first vent route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction to formate provides the reduced carbon entry point; homologation and ketoacid expansion lead to alpha-ketoglutarate and onward to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-pyruvate vent route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate and reduced carbon chemistry produce pyruvate, which expands into alpha-ketoglutarate before entering the glutamate route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-centered convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Multiple vent products converge at pyruvate, then continue through alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate-derived cyclization to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Mild H2/NH3 Ni-mineral proline precursor route\",\n      \"description\": \"At 22C and pH 8, Ni-bearing mineral systems produce glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate; nonenzymatic downstream steps convert it to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Miller-Urey discharge route\",\n      \"description\": \"High-energy spark chemistry in reduced gas mixtures produces trace proline directly, independently of the glutamate pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photochemistry to direct proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN photochemistry builds a precursor pool that under UV-rich, radical conditions yields trace proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge plus HCN-surface photochemical route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark chemistry supplies HCN to the surface pool; subsequent UV/mineral processing forms amine-rich intermediates and then proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-environment hybrid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies ketoacid hubs while surface chemistry supplies concentrated HCN and photochemical precursor pools; both inventories converge in biochemical settings where glutamate-derived cyclization furnishes proline and surface-derived trace proline is incorporated directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network uses literature-grounded prebiotic routes that converge on L-proline through the best-supported precursor logic: hydrothermal H2-driven formation of alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate, followed by nonenzymatic reduction/cyclization through glutamate semialdehyde and Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate, plus direct low-yield mixed-chemistry production in lightning/discharge and UV-rich surface settings. Surface environments also supply HCN-derived nitrogen chemistry, concentration, phosphorylation/condensation context, and mineral adsorption that preserves intermediates and enables downstream biochemical assembly. Because the literature shows no dedicated high-yield proline synthesis, several reactions are explicitly marked as speculative-but-necessary connectors consistent with the reported alphaKG -> glutamate -> glutamate-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline framework.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid/acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "Delta1-pyrroline-