: "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent interface, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S surfaces generate acetyl-like intermediates that hydrolyze to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate generation from reduced C1 species under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis matches the acetyl-CoA analog logic discussed for vent chemistry and supplies a C2 node for pyruvate and alpha-ketoglutarate emergence. Supported by Fe-S carbon fixation concepts in Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997 and contextualized in Somorjai et al., 2023."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type and hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Surface reduction of CO2/CO-derived intermediates followed by C-C coupling yields small aldehydes including glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite and reduced iron is a plausible source of aldehydes used later in surface sugar and nitrile chemistry. This is used here as a connector to literature-supported HCN-rich and mixed-chemistry contexts. Supported generally by hydrothermal carbonyl synthesis literature and integrated prebiotic network logic in Kaur et al., 2024 and Somorjai et al., 2023."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Reductive C1/C2 assimilation and mineral-mediated carboxylation/condensation generate alpha-keto acid functionality, producing pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a central hydrothermal hub in protometabolic analogs and is a required precursor to larger alpha-keto acids. This reaction is a network-level connector consistent with H2-driven prebiotic carbon fixation and ketoacid generation. Supported by prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog chemistry in Kaur et al., 2024 and vent-based carbon fixation rationale in Somorjai et al., 2023."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal and meteoritic analog alpha-ketoglutarate formation", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing mineral surface associated with pyrite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8, H2-accessible, meteorite-powder or Ni-rich mineral analog context"}, "mechanism": "Reductive aldol-like network expansion from smaller carbonyls and ketoacids gives larger alpha-keto acids including alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) experimentally demonstrated an H2/NH4+-driven prebiotic Krebs cycle analog over Ni or meteorite powder at 22C and pH 8 producing biological ketoacids and amino acids including glutamate from alphaKG. This network therefore includes alphaKG as a justified hydrothermal-to-mild aqueous hub, though exact stepwise assembly from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde is a necessary connector rather than directly isolated. Supported by Kaur et al., 2024."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing minera