nce >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Proline\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network uses literature-grounded prebiotic routes that converge on L-proline through the best-supported precursor logic: hydrothermal H2-driven formation of alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate, followed by nonenzymatic reduction/cyclization through glutamate semialdehyde and Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate, plus direct low-yield mixed-chemistry production in lightning/discharge and UV-rich surface settings. Surface environments also supply HCN-derived nitrogen chemistry, concentration, phosphorylation/condensation context, and mineral adsorption that preserves intermediates and enables downstream biochemical assembly. Because the literature shows no dedicated high-yield proline synthesis, several reactions are explicitly marked as speculative-but-necessary connectors consistent with the reported alphaKG -> glutamate -> glutamate-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline framework.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4O2 (acetic acid/acetate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H6O3 (pyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C5H6O5 (alpha-ketoglutaric acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C5H9NO4 (glutamic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C5H9NO3 (glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C5H7NO2 (Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C5H9NO2 (L-proline) [target]\n  - mol_014: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C5H12N2 (butylamine precursor pool) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_005, mol_002, mol_001 -> mol_006 (Hydrothermal formate homologation to acetate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Fischer-Tropsch-type and hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry to glycolaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_005, mol_006, mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_008, mol_007, mol_001 -> mol_009 (Hydrothermal and meteoritic analog alpha-ketoglutarate formation) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_009, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_010 (Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_010, mol_002 -> mol_011 (Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_008: mol_011 -> mol_012 (Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to P5C) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_009: mol_012, mol_002 -> mol_013 (Reduction of P5C to L-proline) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_010: mol_001, mol_003 -> mol_004, mol_013 (Surface lightning/discharge synthesis of HCN-rich precursor pool and trace proline) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_004 -> mol_014, mol_015 (Surface UV nitrile chemistry from HCN to formamide and amine-rich precursor pool) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_015 -> mol_013 (UV-ice radical route from butylamine-like precursor pool to trace proline) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Canonical hydrothermal glutamate route (8 steps)\n  - P2: Glycolaldehyde-assisted protometabolic route (6 steps)\n  - P3: Formate-first vent route (6 steps)\n  - P4: Acetate-pyruvate vent route (7 steps)\n  - P5: Pyruvate-centered convergence route (7 steps)\n  - P6: Mild H2/NH3 Ni-mineral proline precursor route (5 steps)\n  - P7: Direct Miller-Urey discharge route (1 steps)\n  - P8: HCN photochemistry to direct proline route (2 steps)\n  - P9: Discharge plus HCN-surface photochemical route (3 steps)\n  - P10: Cross-environment hybrid route (8 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_008, mol_009, mol_010, mol_012\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\