{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T16:03:56.608396", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.75\n- Feedback: The network is topologically solid and tells a coherent prebiotic story, with adequate node counts, multiple hubs, and several convergent branches. It successfully connects hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, and it reaches the target molecule by more than one route. The strongest aspect is literature awareness: it correctly identifies that direct proline synthesis is poorly supported except for trace formation in spark-discharge and broad mixed-chemistry settings, and it uses the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline logic emphasized in the literature. The main weaknesses are chemical support and strict literature alignment for several connector reactions. Alpha-ketoglutarate formation from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde/CO2 is not strongly established in the provided sources, glutamate-to-semialdehyde reduction is acknowledged in the literature as plausible but remains experimentally underdemonstrated, and assignment of specifically L-proline is not justified because the reported abiotic routes are generally racemic or unspecified. The surface HCN-to-butylamine precursor step is also too compressed and speculative. Additionally, the provided summary omits the required per-reaction mineral agents, which is a schema and environmental-detail deficiency. Overall, this is a good exploratory network with one approved literature-backed direct route, but the full network as a high-confidence synthesis map falls below approval threshold.\n- Issues: ['This is the strongest conceptual route because it follows the literature-supported precursor logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline. Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate is well aligned with Kaur et al. 2024, and spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C is chemically reasonable. The main weakness is that alpha-ketoglutarate formation from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde/CO2 is not well established under the stated hydrothermal conditions, and the reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde is speculative and likely the bottleneck. The final reduction of P5C to proline is plausible but not specifically demonstrated prebiotically for this system. Overall, pathway logic is good but key connector steps remain under-supported.', 'The pathway is chemically connected but relies heavily on a glycolaldehyde-assisted route to alpha-ketoglutarate that is only weakly grounded in the provided literature. Glycolaldehyde is a useful carbonyl hub, but using it to reach alpha-ketoglutarate in vent chemistry is speculative. Downstream glutamate/P5C/proline logic remains reasonable. This route is less literature-secure than the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate-centered route.', 'The formate-first vent route is plausible at the early stages, as CO2 reduction to formate and homologation toward acetate are well aligned with hydrothermal mineral catalysis literature. However, the transition from small reduced carbon products to pyruvate and especially alpha-ketoglutarate is not strongly demonstrated for this exact system. The downstream amino-acid branch is better grounded than the upstream carbon-skeleton assembly.', 'This route benefits from plausible acetate chemistry but suffers from the same under-supported carbon-chain extension to alpha-ketoglutarate. The canonical precursor sequence to proline is coherent, yet too much of the carbon-skeleton construction is inferred rather than literature-established. Good network continuity, but weak empirical grounding in the midstream steps.', 'Pyruvate is a sensible hub in prebiotic protometabolic chemistry, and using it as a convergence node is a topological strength. However, pyruvate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate is the least secure step in the route. Once alpha-ketoglutarate is granted, the route becomes substantially more plausible. As drawn, this pathway is coherent but dependent on a speculative bottleneck.', 'This is a compact precursor-to-target route and aligns best with the key literature inference that alpha-ketoglutarate can be aminated to glutamate under H2/NH3 with Ni-containing catalysts. The weakness remains the nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde, which is discussed as chemically feasible in the literature but not strongly demonstrated experimentally. This route is one of the better ones but still falls short of approval because the central reduction bottleneck is unresolved.', \"The UV-ice/radical route has some literature support through interstellar ice experiments and the proposed butylamine-related radical chemistry discussed by Simionato et al. However, the network's conversion of HCN directly into formamide plus a generic butylamine precursor pool is too compressed and speculative. The final UV route to proline is plausible in broad mixed photochemistry but not sufficiently defined here.\", \"This hybrid surface route benefits from beginning with a documented spark-discharge source of trace proline and HCN-rich products, but the HCN-to-butylamine precursor pool remains weakly specified. The overall idea of mixed discharge plus photochemical processing is consistent with the literature's broad mixed-chemistry picture, yet the exact intermediates are too generic for high confidence.\", 'This pathway best satisfies the requested cross-environment story, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation and amino-acid precursor generation with surface HCN chemistry and biochemical completion. Topologically it is strong and environmentally well integrated. Chemically, however, it inherits the weakest hydrothermal bottlenecks, especially alpha-ketoglutarate formation and glutamate reduction. It is a good systems-level pathway but not yet a strongly evidenced synthetic route.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network centers L-proline synthesis on the literature-backed precursor sequence alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate -> proline, while explicitly acknowledging that the decisive bottlenecks are the nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde and the low-yield/nonselective nature of direct abiotic proline formation. To satisfy the requirement for 10 pathways without over-claiming unsupported chemistry, the network uses multiple environmental entry points documented in the literature: hydrothermal H2/NH4+/Ni-like reductive amination to glutamate, direct spark-discharge formation of proline, UV-ice mixed photochemistry yielding proline, meteoritic delivery of proline, and broad nitrile-rich surface chemistry that plausibly feeds glutamate/P5C-class intermediates. Surface and biochemical steps are used mainly for concentration, sorption, cyclization, reduction, and preservation rather than inventing unsupported dedicated proline routes. Because abiotic syntheses reported in the literature are racemic or unspecified, the target is labeled L-proline as requested, but the network notes that prebiotic production is expected to be racemic and that L-enrichment is unresolved.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-hydroxyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H11N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butan-1-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"butylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H11N/c1-2-3-4-5/h2-5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"meteoritic proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of alpha-ketoglutarate in H2-driven protometabolic vent network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high H2 headspace / hydrothermal analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing mineral analog on Fe-S surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 8; H2 and NH4Cl used in protometabolic amino-acid-generating network; alpha-ketoglutarate treated as available node from the reported Krebs-cycle analog network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2-driven reductive protometabolic carbon-fixation network supplies alpha-ketoglutarate as a central ketoacid intermediate under metal-rich catalytic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. 2024 demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog in which alpha-ketoglutarate is part of the H2-driven ketoacid network under mild aqueous conditions with nickel or meteoritic catalysts. The exact standalone synthesis of alpha-ketoglutarate from CO2 was not isolated in the proline literature packet, so this node is included as a literature-grounded network intermediate rather than a claimed single-step yield. Fe-S mineral agents are added to place the chemistry in the required hydrothermal vent context, consistent with Fe-S catalysis emphasized by Somorjai et al. 2023 and vent models, but this specific coupling remains partly inferential. (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal H2/NH3 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high H2 headspace / hydrothermal analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing mineral analog associated with Fe-S surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8; NH4Cl 6-150 mM; mild aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-catalyzed reductive amination converts the alpha-keto acid to the corresponding amino acid using H2 as reductant and ammonium/ammonia as nitrogen source.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest literature-supported upstream step toward proline. Kaur et al. 2024 directly showed H2/NH4+-driven formation of amino acids from biological ketoacids over Ni or meteorite powder at 22 degrees C and pH 8, including glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate. The present network embeds that chemistry in an Fe-S vent setting because the synthesis brief requires hydrothermal mineral agents; pyrite/greigite are therefore specified as contextual vent minerals while the key catalytic precedent remains Ni-rich mineral chemistry. (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"reducing mineral interface plausible but not established as required here\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"moderate pH; prolonged reduction under reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the gamma-carboxyl functionality of glutamate yields the semialdehyde precursor required for spontaneous ring closure.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Somorjai et al. 2023 explicitly discuss the canonical nonenzymatic logic glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline as chemically feasible in origin-of-biosynthesis arguments, but dedicated prebiotic experimental demonstration remains lacking. This reaction is therefore included as a necessary, literature-identified bottleneck and should be considered speculative but directly motivated by the provided review. (Somorjai et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intramolecular cyclization in moderate pH solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular condensation of the amino aldehyde gives the 5-membered cyclic imine/carboxylate P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C is the least controversial part of the canonical precursor logic and is specifically identified in the research summary as the natural consequence of semialdehyde formation. This step follows the route discussed by Somorjai et al. 2023 for prebiotic analogs of biosynthetic pathways. (Somorjai et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"metal/reducing surface plausible\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing environment; no molecular oxygen\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C affords proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The final P5C-to-proline reduction is part of the canonical sequence highlighted in the literature packet. However, no dedicated prebiotic experiment in the supplied sources isolated this exact step under early Earth conditions, so it remains a plausible completion step rather than a firmly demonstrated route. The target is requested as L-proline, but available prebiotic evidence is racemic or unspecified, so stereochemical enrichment is unresolved. (Somorjai et al., 2023; Ring et al., 1972; Simionato et al., 2018)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge synthesis of hydrogen cyanide and mixed organonitrogen pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~298K bulk flask\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge plus mineral surfaces in collection environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"high-voltage spark around 7000 V; CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge generates radicals and cyanide-bearing products, furnishing an HCN-rich precursor pool that feeds later mixed chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ring et al. 1972 showed Miller-type spark discharge of CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3 gives a complex amino-acid mixture including proline. HCN is a standard and unavoidable product class in such discharge chemistry and is also explicitly highlighted in the research summary as a likely precursor pool for more complex nitrogenous organics. The mineral agents here represent surface capture/concentration rather than direct spark catalysis, included to satisfy the required surface-mineral annotation. (Ring et al., 1972; Simionato et al., 2018)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge direct formation of proline from reduced primitive atmosphere mixture\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~298K bulk flask\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"high-voltage spark around 7000 V; reduced gas mixture; trace yield in complex product mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Plasma radical chemistry produces complex carbon-nitrogen intermediates that ultimately hydrolyze and rearrange to minor amounts of proline in the product mixture.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the only direct experimental abiotic route to proline explicitly documented in the supplied literature set. Ring et al. 1972 identified proline qualitatively among amino acids formed in spark-discharge experiments. Yield is low and stereochemistry unresolved, but it is a firm empirical route and therefore must be included. Mineral agents are assigned as plausible collection/concentration surfaces in subaerial settings rather than as the primary energy source. (Ring et al., 1972)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-ice photochemistry of nitrile-rich organics to butylamine-type precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<100K in ice analogs; post-delivery processing variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low in ice analogs / ambient after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photons\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"mixed interstellar/cometary ice analog radical chemistry; mapped here as exogenous surface input after delivery\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of simple ices generates radicals that can build larger amines, including butylamine-like intermediates implicated in proline formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. 2018 summarize interstellar ice analog work in which UV photolysis of simple ices yields proline and discuss a radical-radical mechanism involving butylamine-like precursors. The exact conversion from HCN-rich simple mixtures to butylamine is not isolated in the proline-specific literature and is therefore represented as a mixed-chemistry precursor step with explicit uncertainty. It is included because the user requested multiple pathways but the literature specifically identifies butylamine-related radical routes. Surface mineral agents are again contextual for post-deposition concentration/processing rather than the original interstellar photolysis. (Simionato et al., 2018)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-ice radical conversion of butylamine-type precursor to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<100K in ice analogs; ambient after delivery possible\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low in ice analogs / ambient after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photons\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"radical-radical chemistry in irradiated ices; low yield and mixed products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photogenerated radicals and intramolecular capture produce cyclic amino-acid skeletons, yielding proline among complex products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. 2018 discuss proline formation in simulated interstellar ices and note proposed radical pathways from butylamine-type precursors. This is not a clean dedicated reaction in early-Earth aqueous chemistry, but it is directly anchored in the supplied literature as one of the few non-spark routes associated with proline itself. (Simionato et al., 2018)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteoritic delivery of abiotic proline to surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"pyrite-like impact-associated sulfide mineral surfaces\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"delivery from carbonaceous meteorites to ponds, shorelines, or sediments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Exogenous transfer introduces preformed proline synthesized in parent-body or interstellar chemistry into planetary surface environments.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. 2018 reported proline in carbonaceous meteorites such as Murchison and Murray, demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry outside Earth can deliver the amino acid. This is not synthesis on Earth but is an essential literature-supported environmental source feeding prebiotic networks. Mineral agents represent adsorption and preservation surfaces upon landing, consistent with Cueto-Diaz et al. 2023 on mineral sorption of proline. (Simionato et al., 2018; Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral-assisted sorption, concentration, and preservation of proline in surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles; adsorption on clay/mineral interfaces; concentration from dilute solutions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Adsorption and concentration on mineral surfaces preserve and accumulate proline delivered or synthesized in low yield, making it available to later prebiotic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cueto-Diaz et al. 2023 showed that proline sorbs strongly to mineral surfaces including montmorillonite and Fe-sulfide-related materials. This step is not synthesis in the strictest sense, but the literature makes clear that concentration/preservation is critical because direct proline yields are very low. The network uses this step to connect sparse surface proline production to the broader prebiotic pool. (Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical pool integration of surface or exogenous proline into the target L-proline node\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pool concentration, membrane partitioning, and selection without demonstrated enantioselection\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Delivered racemic/unspecified proline enters prebiotic solution and is retained in the available amino-acid inventory represented by the target node.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The target node is specified as L-proline, but the supplied literature does not establish abiotic enantioselective synthesis. This integration step therefore represents incorporation of preformed proline into the prebiotic amino-acid pool rather than a justified stereoselective conversion. The unresolved homochirality issue is explicitly highlighted in the research summary and is not solved here. (Simionato et al., 2018; Ring et al., 1972)\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate to proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"The most literature-aligned endogenous route: hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate, then reduced to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde, cyclized to P5C, and reduced to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glutamate-first route\",\n      \"description\": \"Assumes alpha-ketoglutarate is available from the protometabolic network and emphasizes the experimentally supported H2/NH3 reductive amination to glutamate before the canonical cyclization sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Semialdehyde-entry canonical closure route\",\n      \"description\": \"If glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde is generated under reducing prebiotic conditions, spontaneous cyclization to P5C and reduction yields proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"P5C reduction route\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest endogenous completion route once the cyclic imine P5C has formed.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Miller-Urey spark route to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct low-yield proline formation in electric-discharge experiments from reduced atmospheric gases.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-derived HCN mixed chemistry feeding direct proline pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark discharge first generates an HCN-rich precursor pool and, in the same general mixed-discharge chemistry, also produces proline that is then concentrated on minerals.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-ice butylamine-mediated route\",\n      \"description\": \"Photochemical radical chemistry in nitrile-rich ices generates butylamine-like intermediates that convert to proline, which is then retained on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-centered photochemical route to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN serves as the surface photochemical hub entering UV-driven mixed chemistry that yields butylamine-like intermediates and then proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteoritic delivery route\",\n      \"description\": \"Proline formed in extraterrestrial chemistry is delivered by meteorites and incorporated into prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-to-biochemical preservation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Any surface-generated proline is first concentrated and preserved on mineral surfaces and then passed into the biochemical amino-acid inventory represented by the target node.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network centers L-proline synthesis on the literature-backed precursor sequence alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate -> proline, while explicitly acknowledging that the decisive bottlenecks are the nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde and the low-yield/nonselective nature of direct abiotic proline formation. To satisfy the requirement for 10 pathways without over-claiming unsupported chemistry, the network uses multiple environmental entry points documented in the literature: hydrothermal H2/NH4+/Ni-like reductive amination to glutamate, direct spark-discharge formation of proline, UV-ice mixed photochemistry yielding proline, meteoritic delivery of proline, and broad nitrile-rich surface chemistry that plausibly feeds glutamate/P5C-class intermediates. Surface and biochemical steps are used mainly for concentration, sorption, cyclization, reduction, and preservation rather than inventing unsupported dedicated proline routes. Because abiotic syntheses reported in the literature are racemic or unspecified, the target is labeled L-proline as requested, but the network notes that prebiotic production is expected to be racemic and that L-enrichment is unresolved.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-hydroxyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H11N", "iupac_name": "butan-1-amine", "common_name": "butylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H11N/c1-2-3-4-5/h2-5H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "meteoritic proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of alpha-ketoglutarate in H2-driven protometabolic vent network", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "high H2 headspace / hydrothermal analog", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing mineral analog on Fe-S surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 8; H2 and NH4Cl used in protometabolic amino-acid-generating network; alpha-ketoglutarate treated as available node from the reported Krebs-cycle analog network"}, "mechanism": "H2-driven reductive protometabolic carbon-fixation network supplies alpha-ketoglutarate as a central ketoacid intermediate under metal-rich catalytic conditions.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. 2024 demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog in which alpha-ketoglutarate is part of the H2-driven ketoacid network under mild aqueous conditions with nickel or meteoritic catalysts. The exact standalone synthesis of alpha-ketoglutarate from CO2 was not isolated in the proline literature packet, so this node is included as a literature-grounded network intermediate rather than a claimed single-step yield. Fe-S mineral agents are added to place the chemistry in the required hydrothermal vent context, consistent with Fe-S catalysis emphasized by Somorjai et al. 2023 and vent models, but this specific coupling remains partly inferential. (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal H2/NH3 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "high H2 headspace / hydrothermal analog", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing mineral analog associated with Fe-S surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8; NH4Cl 6-150 mM; mild aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "Metal-catalyzed reductive amination converts the alpha-keto acid to the corresponding amino acid using H2 as reductant and ammonium/ammonia as nitrogen source.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest literature-supported upstream step toward proline. Kaur et al. 2024 directly showed H2/NH4+-driven formation of amino acids from biological ketoacids over Ni or meteorite powder at 22 degrees C and pH 8, including glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate. The present network embeds that chemistry in an Fe-S vent setting because the synthesis brief requires hydrothermal mineral agents; pyrite/greigite are therefore specified as contextual vent minerals while the key catalytic precedent remains Ni-rich mineral chemistry. (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["none"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": "reducing mineral interface plausible but not established as required here", "aqueous": "true", "other": "moderate pH; prolonged reduction under reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Reduction of the gamma-carboxyl functionality of glutamate yields the semialdehyde precursor required for spontaneous ring closure.", "reasoning": "Somorjai et al. 2023 explicitly discuss the canonical nonenzymatic logic glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline as chemically feasible in origin-of-biosynthesis arguments, but dedicated prebiotic experimental demonstration remains lacking. This reaction is therefore included as a necessary, literature-identified bottleneck and should be considered speculative but directly motivated by the provided review. (Somorjai et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["none"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-373K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "intramolecular cyclization in moderate pH solution"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular condensation of the amino aldehyde gives the 5-membered cyclic imine/carboxylate P5C.", "reasoning": "The spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C is the least controversial part of the canonical precursor logic and is specifically identified in the research summary as the natural consequence of semialdehyde formation. This step follows the route discussed by Somorjai et al. 2023 for prebiotic analogs of biosynthetic pathways. (Somorjai et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reduction of Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["none"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": "metal/reducing surface plausible", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing environment; no molecular oxygen"}, "mechanism": "Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C affords proline.", "reasoning": "The final P5C-to-proline reduction is part of the canonical sequence highlighted in the literature packet. However, no dedicated prebiotic experiment in the supplied sources isolated this exact step under early Earth conditions, so it remains a plausible completion step rather than a firmly demonstrated route. The target is requested as L-proline, but available prebiotic evidence is racemic or unspecified, so stereochemical enrichment is unresolved. (Somorjai et al., 2023; Ring et al., 1972; Simionato et al., 2018)"}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Spark-discharge synthesis of hydrogen cyanide and mixed organonitrogen pool", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~298K bulk flask", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electric discharge plus mineral surfaces in collection environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high-voltage spark around 7000 V; CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates radicals and cyanide-bearing products, furnishing an HCN-rich precursor pool that feeds later mixed chemistry.", "reasoning": "Ring et al. 1972 showed Miller-type spark discharge of CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3 gives a complex amino-acid mixture including proline. HCN is a standard and unavoidable product class in such discharge chemistry and is also explicitly highlighted in the research summary as a likely precursor pool for more complex nitrogenous organics. The mineral agents here represent surface capture/concentration rather than direct spark catalysis, included to satisfy the required surface-mineral annotation. (Ring et al., 1972; Simionato et al., 2018)"}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Spark-discharge direct formation of proline from reduced primitive atmosphere mixture", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~298K bulk flask", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electric discharge", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high-voltage spark around 7000 V; reduced gas mixture; trace yield in complex product mixture"}, "mechanism": "Plasma radical chemistry produces complex carbon-nitrogen intermediates that ultimately hydrolyze and rearrange to minor amounts of proline in the product mixture.", "reasoning": "This is the only direct experimental abiotic route to proline explicitly documented in the supplied literature set. Ring et al. 1972 identified proline qualitatively among amino acids formed in spark-discharge experiments. Yield is low and stereochemistry unresolved, but it is a firm empirical route and therefore must be included. Mineral agents are assigned as plausible collection/concentration surfaces in subaerial settings rather than as the primary energy source. (Ring et al., 1972)"}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "UV-ice photochemistry of nitrile-rich organics to butylamine-type precursor", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "<100K in ice analogs; post-delivery processing variable", "pressure": "low in ice analogs / ambient after deposition", "catalyst": "UV photons", "aqueous": "false", "other": "mixed interstellar/cometary ice analog radical chemistry; mapped here as exogenous surface input after delivery"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of simple ices generates radicals that can build larger amines, including butylamine-like intermediates implicated in proline formation.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. 2018 summarize interstellar ice analog work in which UV photolysis of simple ices yields proline and discuss a radical-radical mechanism involving butylamine-like precursors. The exact conversion from HCN-rich simple mixtures to butylamine is not isolated in the proline-specific literature and is therefore represented as a mixed-chemistry precursor step with explicit uncertainty. It is included because the user requested multiple pathways but the literature specifically identifies butylamine-related radical routes. Surface mineral agents are again contextual for post-deposition concentration/processing rather than the original interstellar photolysis. (Simionato et al., 2018)"}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "UV-ice radical conversion of butylamine-type precursor to proline", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "<100K in ice analogs; ambient after delivery possible", "pressure": "low in ice analogs / ambient after deposition", "catalyst": "UV photons", "aqueous": "false", "other": "radical-radical chemistry in irradiated ices; low yield and mixed products"}, "mechanism": "Photogenerated radicals and intramolecular capture produce cyclic amino-acid skeletons, yielding proline among complex products.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. 2018 discuss proline formation in simulated interstellar ices and note proposed radical pathways from butylamine-type precursors. This is not a clean dedicated reaction in early-Earth aqueous chemistry, but it is directly anchored in the supplied literature as one of the few non-spark routes associated with proline itself. (Simionato et al., 2018)"}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Meteoritic delivery of abiotic proline to surface pools", "inputs": [], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "pyrite-like impact-associated sulfide mineral surfaces"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "1 atm after deposition", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "delivery from carbonaceous meteorites to ponds, shorelines, or sediments"}, "mechanism": "Exogenous transfer introduces preformed proline synthesized in parent-body or interstellar chemistry into planetary surface environments.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. 2018 reported proline in carbonaceous meteorites such as Murchison and Murray, demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry outside Earth can deliver the amino acid. This is not synthesis on Earth but is an essential literature-supported environmental source feeding prebiotic networks. Mineral agents represent adsorption and preservation surfaces upon landing, consistent with Cueto-Diaz et al. 2023 on mineral sorption of proline. (Simionato et al., 2018; Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Mineral-assisted sorption, concentration, and preservation of proline in surface pools", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles; adsorption on clay/mineral interfaces; concentration from dilute solutions"}, "mechanism": "Adsorption and concentration on mineral surfaces preserve and accumulate proline delivered or synthesized in low yield, making it available to later prebiotic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Cueto-Diaz et al. 2023 showed that proline sorbs strongly to mineral surfaces including montmorillonite and Fe-sulfide-related materials. This step is not synthesis in the strictest sense, but the literature makes clear that concentration/preservation is critical because direct proline yields are very low. The network uses this step to connect sparse surface proline production to the broader prebiotic pool. (Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023)"}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical pool integration of surface or exogenous proline into the target L-proline node", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["none"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-350K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pool concentration, membrane partitioning, and selection without demonstrated enantioselection"}, "mechanism": "Delivered racemic/unspecified proline enters prebiotic solution and is retained in the available amino-acid inventory represented by the target node.", "reasoning": "The target node is specified as L-proline, but the supplied literature does not establish abiotic enantioselective synthesis. This integration step therefore represents incorporation of preformed proline into the prebiotic amino-acid pool rather than a justified stereoselective conversion. The unresolved homochirality issue is explicitly highlighted in the research summary and is not solved here. (Simionato et al., 2018; Ring et al., 1972)"}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate to proline route", "description": "The most literature-aligned endogenous route: hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate, then reduced to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde, cyclized to P5C, and reduced to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal glutamate-first route", "description": "Assumes alpha-ketoglutarate is available from the protometabolic network and emphasizes the experimentally supported H2/NH3 reductive amination to glutamate before the canonical cyclization sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Semialdehyde-entry canonical closure route", "description": "If glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde is generated under reducing prebiotic conditions, spontaneous cyclization to P5C and reduction yields proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "P5C reduction route", "d