biotically.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit reducing conditions and a catalyst such as FeS, pyrite, or Ni-bearing mineral to support the reduction.\",\n        \"Distinguish between theoretical plausibility and demonstrated prebiotic evidence.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.22\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.69,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.71,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.61,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.67,\n      \"feedback\": \"The direct spark-discharge route is one of the strongest literature-supported entries because proline has indeed been observed as a minor component in Miller-type discharge experiments. The major flaw is rxn_011, which converts generic or racemic proline to the target L-proline via sorption/preservation; sorption does not synthesize or resolve enantiomerically pure L-proline. Therefore the pathway reaches proline, but not convincingly L-proline.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent the spark product as racemic proline rather than L-proline unless an enantioenrichment mechanism is provided.\",\n        \"Use the final node as 'proline' or annotate unresolved chirality explicitly.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.73,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.22\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.61,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.58,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.72,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.6,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is not very coherent because rxn_006 generates HCN but does not materially feed rxn_007, which already produces proline directly from the spark mixture. The branch is therefore narratively dense but graph-theoretically and chemically weak as a true causal route. The chirality issue remains unresolved in the final step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Separate the direct spark route from the HCN-centered route unless HCN is actually used in a downstream proline-forming reaction.\",\n        \"Avoid counting parallel outputs from the same discharge as sequential causation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.44,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.47,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.22\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.38,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.48,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.63,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.56,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.44,\n      \"feedback\": \"This UV-ice butylamine-mediated route reflects literature discussion that butylamine-like precursors may participate in proline formation in irradiated ices, but the specific sequence HCN -> butylamine -> proline is not strongly established. It is much more speculative than the network implies. The final conversion to L-proline via sorption is also invalid as a synthetic or chiral-resolution step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Downgrade this route to a speculative photochemical branch.\",\n        \"Use low-temperature ice photolysis conditions if retained, rather than generic surface chemistry.\",\n        \"Do not infer L-selectivity from concentration or preservation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.73,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.44,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.47\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.47,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.52,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.66,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.58,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.5,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN as a hub is literature-relevant, but the pathway from HCN to butylamine-type precursor to proline is only weakly supported. The research explicitly notes that nitrile-rich paths to proline are plausible but experimentally limited. This should be treated as a hypothesis-generating branch, not a validated pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State that the pathway is conjectural and supported only indirectly by Titan/ice photochemistry discussions.\",\n        \"Include a more explicit C4/C5 nitrile intermediate if literature support is available.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.2\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.64,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.7,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.57,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.66,\n      \"feedback\": \"Meteorite delivery of proline is strongly supported by the literature and is one of the best-grounded entries in the network. However, the second step merely maps delivered proline into an L-proline target node without any plausible chiral selection mechanism. Thus this is a credible source of abiotic proline, but not of L-proline specifically.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Rename the target as proline/racemic proline, or add a genuine enantioenrichment process if L-proline must be retained.\",\n        \"Clarify that meteorites deliver low concentrations and require concentration/preservation rather than stereospecific conversion.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.22,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.2\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.42,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.45,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.69,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.52,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.46,\n      \"feedback\": \"This preservation/integration pathway overstates what concentration and pool transfer can accomplish. Surface sorption and biochemical integration are reasonable for preservation and availability, but they do not create L-proline from nonchiral or racemic sources. As written, the route conflates transport with synthesis.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use preservation/integration steps only to move existing proline between environments, not to justify formation of L-proline.\",\n        \"Separate availability from synthesis and stereochemical resolution.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically adequate and reasonably connected, with a clear central motif around alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde, and P5C. It also aligns fairly well with the literature's overall message: proline is difficult prebiotically, direct evidence is strongest for spark-discharge, UV-ice, and meteoritic occurrence, and the canonical glutamate/P5C route is plausible but not experimentally established as a full abiotic sequence. Major weaknesses reduce confidence. First, the target is defined as L-proline even though the cited literature supports only racemic or unspecified abiotic proline; the network's final 'conversion' steps from proline to L-proline via sorption or pool integration are chemically invalid. Second, several key reactions lack the required mineral-agent specification for hydrothermal and surface contexts, which is a schema and environmental interconnection failure. Third, alpha-ketoglutarate formation from CO2 + H2 is underjustified, and the glutamate-to-semialdehyde reduction remains the major unsupported bottleneck. Fourth, some pathways are inflated by splitting partial segments or by treating parallel source terms as sequential pathways. Literature alignment is moderate to good in spirit but uneven in execution: the network correctly centers known sources and acknowledges bottlenecks, yet overstates confidence in speculative nitrile and butylamine routes and mishandles chirality.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.78,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.74\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.38, "rxn_002": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.28, "rxn_004": 0.87, "rxn_005": 0.55}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.59, "pathway_coherence": 0.74, "environmental_progression": 0.68, "target_achievement": 0.72, "overall_confidence": 0.66, "feedback": "This is the most chemically structured route and aligns with the literature-recognized biological logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline. However, the weakest points are the unsupported prebiotic generation of alpha-ketoglutarate from only CO2 + H2 and the highly speculative nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to the gamma-semialdehyde. Cyclization of the semialdehyde to P5C is plausible, and final reduction of P5C to proline is conceivable, but overall this remains a low-evidence route rather than an experimentally demonstrated complete prebiotic pathway.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005"], "suggestions": ["Specify actual hydrothermal mineral agents and conditions for alpha-ketoglutarate formation and note that this step is protometabolic and indirect rather than directly establi