{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T16:06:42.983793", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nL-Proline: Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\nKnown Prebiotic Routes: L-Proline is a secondary (cyclic) amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis is challenging. The only direct evidence of abiotic proline formation comes from classic spark-discharge (Miller\u2013Urey) experiments. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) reported that sparking a CH<sub>4</sub>-N<sub>2</sub> gas mixture with H<sub>2</sub>O and traces of NH<sub>3</sub> yields a suite of amino acids, including proline[1]. Other broad simulation studies (e.g. shock heating or UV-irradiation of primitive mixtures) likewise produce complex amino-acid mixtures where proline appears as a minor component[1][2]. Proline has also been detected in carbonaceous meteorites (e.g. Murchison: 622\u20131550 ppb[2]), indicating that prebiotic or extraterrestrial processes can produce proline. In simulated interstellar ices, UV photolysis of simple ices can yield proline \u2013 for example, a radical\u2013radical mechanism from precursors like butylamine has been proposed to account for proline formation under UV irradiation[2]. Astrobiology models (e.g. for Titan) suggest proline can form thermodynamically in HCN-rich, NH<sub>3</sub>-poor environments, but experimental support is limited. Unlike glycine or alanine (readily made by Strecker synthesis), no direct prebiotic Strecker pathway for proline has been demonstrated; that route would require a 4-carbon dialdehyde (succinaldehyde) that has not been shown to form or react under plausible conditions. In summary, only broad, mixed-chemistry experiments (electric discharge, UV, shock, meteorite analogs) have produced proline. Modern work on protometabolic networks (e.g. Kaur et al. 2024) shows H<sub>2</sub>-driven pathways can make many \u03b1-amino acids, but none so far isolate proline specifically[3].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors: Known chemical routes to proline all pass through a 5\u2011carbon intermediate that can cyclize. The canonical biological route is L-glutamate \u2192 L-glutamate-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GS-Ald) \u2192 \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) \u2192 proline. In a prebiotic context, the \u03b1-ketoglutarate (\u03b1KG) ketoacid plus NH<sub>3</sub> would first yield L-glutamate, which upon reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl becomes glutamate semialdehyde; this spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, which can then be reduced to proline[4]. Thus glutamate and \u03b1KG are key precursors. Biochemically, ornithine can also yield proline (via ornithine-\u03b3-semialdehyde to P5C), linking proline to the urea cycle (ornithine itself is from glutamate)[5]. Prebiotic precursors likely include small molecules like NH\u2083, HCN, CO\u2082/HCOO\u2013 and carbonyls. For example, HCN polymerization (cyanosulfidic chemistry) in the presence of NH\u2083 could form amino-imines or aminonitriles that lead to amino acids. In simulated Titan chemistry, nitriles like acrylonitrile and HCN can produce proline and other amino acids without added NH\u2083[6], implying that nitrile precursors (e.g. 4\u2011carbon nitriles) might form proline. Intermediates like butylamine, glyoxylate-derived species, or \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) have been speculated as stepping stones, but experimental confirmation is lacking. In astrochemical ices, radical processes on simple ices (methanol, ammonia, water with UV) have been shown to yield proline[2]. In short, the essential branch-point intermediates are \u03b1KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, plus any alternative aminated C4 skeleton that can cyclize.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions: - Lightning/Discharge: High-energy electric discharges in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083 plasmas generate radicals that recombine into amino acids[1]. No specific mechanism for proline is detailed, but complex radicals likely form a cyclic nitrile/imine that hydrolyzes to proline. Conditions: typical Miller conditions (~ 7000 V, ~25\u00b0C in flask, ambient pressure) with CH\u2084:N\u2082:NH\u2083 and spark. Yields: Ring et al. confirmed proline qualitatively via chromatography[1] (no quantitative yield reported, presumably much lower than simpler amino acids). - Reductive Amination (H\u2082/metal): H<sub>2</sub> and NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup> reacting with \u03b1-keto acids on metal catalysts can produce amino acids[3]. For example, Kaur et al. (2024) showed that Ni (or metal-rich meteorite powder) at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, with H\u2082 and NH\u2084Cl (6\u2013150 mM NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>) converts six biological ketoacids plus glyoxylate into the corresponding amino acids in good yields[3]. This network included reductive amination and reductive aldol steps, resembling core metabolism. It implies \u03b1-ketoglutarate + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate can occur under these mild conditions[3], setting up proline formation via cyclization. - Non-enzymatic Cyclization: If glutamate is formed, the \u03b3-carboxyl can be reduced to glutamate semialdehyde (via H\u2082 or hydrides on Fe\u2013S catalysts), which spontaneously cyclizes to \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate[4]. Subsequently, P5C can be reduced to proline by available reductants (e.g. H<sub>2</sub>/metal). This sequence mimics the enzyme-catalyzed steps but is chemically feasible on mineral catalysts. Philos. Trans. work notes this exact pathway \u201cnon-enzymatically\u201d[4]. Conditions: likely moderate (50\u2013100\u00b0C), with reducing minerals (e.g. FeS) and moderate pH. - Surface/UV Processes: UV photolysis of nitrile-rich ices at low temperatures (<100 K) can induce radical chemistry forming amino acids. For proline, Simionato et al. noted that butylamine (C\u2084H\u2089NH\u2082) in ice photolysis leads to proline formation via radical-radical pathways[2]. On mineral surfaces like pyrite under UV, \u03b1-keto acids can undergo reductive amination (White et al. found D-amino acids formed from \u03b1-keto acids on illuminated FeS\u2082, though not specifically proline). No definitive surface photo-route for proline alone is reported. - Dry\u2013Wet Cycling: Repeated drying and rehydration (evaporitic pool conditions) can condense amino acids into peptides and cyclic dipeptides. Guo et al. (2024) demonstrated that prolinamide (a proline derivative) can form cyclic dipeptides under moderate heat and varying pH[7]. While this is not direct proline synthesis, it highlights that pH oscillations and condensing agents (trimetaphosphate, clay catalysts) can drive amide bond formation. A related idea is that concentrated formamide or hot acid\u2013base pulses could convert simple organics into amino acids (though specific proline yields are not documented).\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces: Iron\u2013sulfur and clay minerals likely facilitate steps toward proline. Montmorillonite clay strongly adsorbs proline (and other amino acids) and catalyzes condensation reactions; experiments show proline binds to montmorillonite and to Fe-sulphide (pyrite) surfaces[8]. Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) and other metal oxides enhance peptide formation[7]. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite, and pyrite surfaces are reductive catalysts (producing H\u2082S/H\u2082) that could enable the required reductive aminations and cyclizations. Trimetaphosphate (P\u2083m) can act as a condensing agent under dry-down conditions[7]. In hydrothermal settings, Ni-bearing minerals (e.g. awaruite in meteorites) provide the Ni catalyst demonstrated by Kaur et al. At 22\u00b0C and pH 8, even trace Ni on pyrite or in meteorite catalysts drives amino acid synthesis[3]. Overall, montmorillonite and metal sulfides (pyrite/greigite) are the most relevant catalysts cited for proline-related chemistry[8][7].\nExperimental Evidence: Key laboratory studies include Miller\u2013Urey electric discharges (Ring et al. 1972) producing proline[1]. Ni-based reductive amination experiments (Kaur et al. 2024) yielded glutamate (from \u03b1KG) and other amino acids[3], implying proline could be downstream. Guo et al. (2024) simulated early Earth ponds and made cyclic dipeptides from amino acids (including proline) using P\u2083m, montmorillonite, and metal ions[7]. Interstellar ice analog experiments show proline formation under UV[2]. Natural evidence comes from meteorites: Simionato et al. (2018) found proline in Murchison and Murray meteorites (ppb levels)[2], demonstrating that nonbiological chemistry yields proline. No isolated prebiotic experiment yet reports a high-yield, dedicated route to proline, and yields in mixed-product experiments are generally low (e.g. Miller\u2019s setup produced only traces). Nonetheless, the combination of meteorite analysis, UV-ice experiments, and catalytic H\u2082-reduction studies indicates multiple contexts can supply proline or its precursors.\n\nFigure: Deep-sea hydrothermal vent (\u201cblack smoker\u201d). Alkaline vents could supply H\u2082 and Fe\u2013S catalysts for proline synthesis via reductive amination (see text) under conditions of moderate temperature and high pressure.\nEnvironmental Context: The most plausible settings for proline synthesis include hydrothermal systems and cyclical wet\u2013dry environments. Alkaline hydrothermal vents (like Lost City) provide H\u2082, CO\u2082 and metal sulfides (e.g. greigite, awaruite) at ~50\u2013120\u00b0C and pH ~9\u201311. In such vents, CO\u2082 reduction yields keto acids (pyruvate, possibly \u03b1KG) and H\u2082-driven chemistry can convert these to amino acids[3]. The embedded image above exemplifies this environment. Shallow tidal or evaporitic pools on land or beachrocks (with day/night or wet/dry cycles) concentrate organics and enable dehydration. Guo et al. showed that pH oscillations (e.g. from mineral acidity changes) and condensing reagents can form peptide bonds[7], suggesting similar cycles could produce proline from amino acid precursors. (By contrast, continuous wet environments lack the concentration effect for condensation.) Finally, interstellar or outer-planetary ices (e.g. on comets or Titan) may produce proline in situ by UV or cosmic-ray chemistry[2], then deliver it to planets by meteorite impacts. This likely accounts for the meteoritic proline detected[2].\n\nFigure: Evaporitic desert lake. Concentrating environments (evaporitic pools, tidal flats) with mineral surfaces (clays, carbonates) could support amino acid condensation. Wet\u2013dry cycles drive peptide bond formation[7], potentially trapping proline and related molecules on surfaces.\nOpen Questions and Challenges: The major gap is no definitive, high-yield prebiotic route to proline has been demonstrated. Key challenges include: Identifying a plausible 4\u2011carbon precursor (e.g. succinaldehyde or equivalent) and mechanism for ring closure. Nonenzymatic cyclization from glutamate relies on having enough reductant and time for P5C formation, which is unproven under realistic conditions. The role of CHN chemistry (HCN polymers, cyanides) in generating proline-like precursors is unclear. Also, most experiments report racemic products and very low proline yields, leaving unresolved how L-proline homochirality emerged (if at all) and why proline yields are much smaller than simple amino acids. In summary, while multiple settings could synthesize proline (lightning, vents, photochemistry), each has significant bottlenecks (e.g. lack of NH\u2083 in some environments, competition with side-reactions, requirement of rare intermediates). Future work must clarify if any of these routes can be optimized, or if alternate chemistries (e.g. novel catalysts or wet\u2013dry protocols) are needed for efficient proline formation.\nSources: Ring et al. 1972 (PNAS)[1]; Kaur et al. 2024 (Chem)[3]; Somorjai et al. 2023 (Phil. Trans. R. Soc.)[4]; Simionato et al. 2018 (Life)[2]; Cueto-D\u00edaz et al. 2023 (Life)[8]; Guo et al. 2024 (Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclim. Palaeoecol.)[7], among others. Each source is cited by author names and year above.\n \n[1]  Prebiotic Synthesis of Hydrophobic and Protein Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2]  The Nitrogen Heterocycle Content of Meteorites and Their Significance for the Origin of Life - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6160977/\n[3] A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2451929424000639\n[4]  Can the origin of biosynthetic routes be explained by a Frankenstein\u2019s monster-like spontaneous assembly of prebiotic reactants? - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12489505/\n[5]  On the Evolutionary History of the Twenty Encoded Amino Acids - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9796705/\n[6] Prebiotic Chemistry Insights for Dragonfly: Thermodynamics of Amino Acid Synthesis in Selk Crater on Titan - Astrobiology\nhttps://astrobiology.com/2025/11/prebiotic-chemistry-insights-for-dragonfly-thermodynamics-of-amino-acid-synthesis-in-selk-crater-on-titan.html\n[7] Local pH variability scenario: Prebiotic synthesis of cyclic dipeptides via prolinamide on the Hadean Earth - ScienceDirect\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018224003912\n[8] A New Approach in Prebiotic Chemistry Studies: Proline Sorption Triggered by Mineral Surfaces Analysed Using XPS | MDPI\nhttps://www.mdpi.com/2075-1729/13/4/908\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.75\n- Feedback: The network is topologically solid and tells a coherent prebiotic story, with adequate node counts, multiple hubs, and several convergent branches. It successfully connects hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, and it reaches the target molecule by more than one route. The strongest aspect is literature awareness: it correctly identifies that direct proline synthesis is poorly supported except for trace formation in spark-discharge and broad mixed-chemistry settings, and it uses the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline logic emphasized in the literature. The main weaknesses are chemical support and strict literature alignment for several connector reactions. Alpha-ketoglutarate formation from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde/CO2 is not strongly established in the provided sources, glutamate-to-semialdehyde reduction is acknowledged in the literature as plausible but remains experimentally underdemonstrated, and assignment of specifically L-proline is not justified because the reported abiotic routes are generally racemic or unspecified. The surface HCN-to-butylamine precursor step is also too compressed and speculative. Additionally, the provided summary omits the required per-reaction mineral agents, which is a schema and environmental-detail deficiency. Overall, this is a good exploratory network with one approved literature-backed direct route, but the full network as a high-confidence synthesis map falls below approval threshold.\n- Issues: ['This is the strongest conceptual route because it follows the literature-supported precursor logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline. Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate is well aligned with Kaur et al. 2024, and spontaneous cyclization of glutamate semialdehyde to P5C is chemically reasonable. The main weakness is that alpha-ketoglutarate formation from pyruvate/glycolaldehyde/CO2 is not well established under the stated hydrothermal conditions, and the reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde is speculative and likely the bottleneck. The final reduction of P5C to proline is plausible but not specifically demonstrated prebiotically for this system. Overall, pathway logic is good but key connector steps remain under-supported.', 'The pathway is chemically connected but relies heavily on a glycolaldehyde-assisted route to alpha-ketoglutarate that is only weakly grounded in the provided literature. Glycolaldehyde is a useful carbonyl hub, but using it to reach alpha-ketoglutarate in vent chemistry is speculative. Downstream glutamate/P5C/proline logic remains reasonable. This route is less literature-secure than the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate-centered route.', 'The formate-first vent route is plausible at the early stages, as CO2 reduction to formate and homologation toward acetate are well aligned with hydrothermal mineral catalysis literature. However, the transition from small reduced carbon products to pyruvate and especially alpha-ketoglutarate is not strongly demonstrated for this exact system. The downstream amino-acid branch is better grounded than the upstream carbon-skeleton assembly.', 'This route benefits from plausible acetate chemistry but suffers from the same under-supported carbon-chain extension to alpha-ketoglutarate. The canonical precursor sequence to proline is coherent, yet too much of the carbon-skeleton construction is inferred rather than literature-established. Good network continuity, but weak empirical grounding in the midstream steps.', 'Pyruvate is a sensible hub in prebiotic protometabolic chemistry, and using it as a convergence node is a topological strength. However, pyruvate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate is the least secure step in the route. Once alpha-ketoglutarate is granted, the route becomes substantially more plausible. As drawn, this pathway is coherent but dependent on a speculative bottleneck.', 'This is a compact precursor-to-target route and aligns best with the key literature inference that alpha-ketoglutarate can be aminated to glutamate under H2/NH3 with Ni-containing catalysts. The weakness remains the nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate semialdehyde, which is discussed as chemically feasible in the literature but not strongly demonstrated experimentally. This route is one of the better ones but still falls short of approval because the central reduction bottleneck is unresolved.', \"The UV-ice/radical route has some literature support through interstellar ice experiments and the proposed butylamine-related radical chemistry discussed by Simionato et al. However, the network's conversion of HCN directly into formamide plus a generic butylamine precursor pool is too compressed and speculative. The final UV route to proline is plausible in broad mixed photochemistry but not sufficiently defined here.\", \"This hybrid surface route benefits from beginning with a documented spark-discharge source of trace proline and HCN-rich products, but the HCN-to-butylamine precursor pool remains weakly specified. The overall idea of mixed discharge plus photochemical processing is consistent with the literature's broad mixed-chemistry picture, yet the exact intermediates are too generic for high confidence.\", 'This pathway best satisfies the requested cross-environment story, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation and amino-acid precursor generation with surface HCN chemistry and biochemical completion. Topologically it is strong and environmentally well integrated. Chemically, however, it inherits the weakest hydrothermal bottlenecks, especially alpha-ketoglutarate formation and glutamate reduction. It is a good systems-level pathway but not yet a strongly evidenced synthetic route.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.63\n- Feedback: The network is topologically adequate and reasonably connected, with a clear central motif around alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde, and P5C. It also aligns fairly well with the literature's overall message: proline is difficult prebiotically, direct evidence is strongest for spark-discharge, UV-ice, and meteoritic occurrence, and the canonical glutamate/P5C route is plausible but not experimentally established as a full abiotic sequence. Major weaknesses reduce confidence. First, the target is defined as L-proline even though the cited literature supports only racemic or unspecified abiotic proline; the network's final 'conversion' steps from proline to L-proline via sorption or pool integration are chemically invalid. Second, several key reactions lack the required mineral-agent specification for hydrothermal and surface contexts, which is a schema and environmental interconnection failure. Third, alpha-ketoglutarate formation from CO2 + H2 is underjustified, and the glutamate-to-semialdehyde reduction remains the major unsupported bottleneck. Fourth, some pathways are inflated by splitting partial segments or by treating parallel source terms as sequential pathways. Literature alignment is moderate to good in spirit but uneven in execution: the network correctly centers known sources and acknowledges bottlenecks, yet overstates confidence in speculative nitrile and butylamine routes and mishandles chirality.\n- Issues: ['This is the most chemically structured route and aligns with the literature-recognized biological logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline. However, the weakest points are the unsupported prebiotic generation of alpha-ketoglutarate from only CO2 + H2 and the highly speculative nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to the gamma-semialdehyde. Cyclization of the semialdehyde to P5C is plausible, and final reduction of P5C to proline is conceivable, but overall this remains a low-evidence route rather than an experimentally demonstrated complete prebiotic pathway.', 'Starting from glutamate improves coherence because Kaur et al. support alpha-keto acid reductive amination to amino acids, including glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate. Still, the core bottleneck remains the reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde, which is not demonstrated prebiotically. This pathway is literature-consistent in outline but weak in decisive chemical evidence.', 'This shortened entry route is coherent once glutamate is assumed available, but it depends almost entirely on the least supported step in the whole network: abiotic selective reduction of glutamate to the gamma-semialdehyde. Cyclization is chemically reasonable; reduction of P5C is plausible but still underdefined.', \"As a one-step closure from P5C to proline, this is chemically plausible in principle, but it is too underspecified to score highly. It reaches the target if P5C is granted, yet that does not solve the network's main challenge of obtaining P5C prebiotically.\", 'The direct spark-discharge route is one of the strongest literature-supported entries because proline has indeed been observed as a minor component in Miller-type discharge experiments. The major flaw is rxn_011, which converts generic or racemic proline to the target L-proline via sorption/preservation; sorption does not synthesize or resolve enantiomerically pure L-proline. Therefore the pathway reaches proline, but not convincingly L-proline.', 'This pathway is not very coherent because rxn_006 generates HCN but does not materially feed rxn_007, which already produces proline directly from the spark mixture. The branch is therefore narratively dense but graph-theoretically and chemically weak as a true causal route. The chirality issue remains unresolved in the final step.', 'This UV-ice butylamine-mediated route reflects literature discussion that butylamine-like precursors may participate in proline formation in irradiated ices, but the specific sequence HCN -> butylamine -> proline is not strongly established. It is much more speculative than the network implies. The final conversion to L-proline via sorption is also invalid as a synthetic or chiral-resolution step.', 'HCN as a hub is literature-relevant, but the pathway from HCN to butylamine-type precursor to proline is only weakly supported. The research explicitly notes that nitrile-rich paths to proline are plausible but experimentally limited. This should be treated as a hypothesis-generating branch, not a validated pathway.', 'Meteorite delivery of proline is strongly supported by the literature and is one of the best-grounded entries in the network. However, the second step merely maps delivered proline into an L-proline target node without any plausible chiral selection mechanism. Thus this is a credible source of abiotic proline, but not of L-proline specifically.', 'This preservation/integration pathway overstates what concentration and pool transfer can accomplish. Surface sorption and biochemical integration are reasonable for preservation and availability, but they do not create L-proline from nonchiral or racemic sources. As written, the route conflates transport with synthesis.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network uses the literature-supported reality that dedicated prebiotic L-proline synthesis is not established and that direct abiotic evidence is strongest from mixed-product spark-discharge, UV-irradiated ice chemistry, and meteoritic delivery, while the most chemically structured downstream route proceeds through the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate -> proline sequence. Because the literature does not justify an abiotic enantioselective synthesis of L-proline, the target is represented as environmental L-proline within a racemic/near-racemic proline pool, with pathways converging on proline-generating chemistry and subsequent incorporation into prebiotic biochemical settings. The network therefore emphasizes literature-backed precursor generation, mixed-chemistry direct formation, mineral-mediated concentration, and a speculative but explicitly labeled nonenzymatic glutamate/P5C branch needed to connect hydrothermal and surface chemistry to the target pool.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n    