      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-395K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite, Ni-bearing vent minerals as analog support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions; H2-rich, anoxic, pH about 8-11; alpha-ketoglutarate inferred within prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise CO2 reduction and carbon-skeleton building in an H2-driven protometabolic network over Fe-S/oxide mineral surfaces produces ketoacids including alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated an H2/NH4+-driven prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog over Ni-rich catalysts yielding biological ketoacid/amino-acid relationships, supporting alpha-ketoglutarate as a central prebiotic intermediate under mild aqueous conditions; hydrothermal Fe-S/mineral adaptation is consistent with vent geochemistry but exact vent-specific alpha-ketoglutarate generation remains partly inferential and therefore this connector is moderately speculative in environment transfer while retaining literature-consistent chemistry (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high H2 availability\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing metal sites associated with Fe-S mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 8; NH4+ 6-150 mM equivalent; anoxic; adapted from Ni-catalyzed prebiotic amination experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia followed by H2-driven reduction on metal/mineral catalytic sites gives glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly grounded in the amino-acid-forming reductive amination chemistry reported by Kaur et al. (2024), who showed alpha-keto acids including alpha-ketoglutarate can be converted to their corresponding amino acids with H2 and NH4+ over nickel-rich catalysts at 22 C and pH 8. Use of Fe-S mineral surfaces here reflects the hydrothermal mineral context highlighted in the report and is chemically plausible, though the exact catalyst composition differs from the original Ni experiments (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"reducing mineral interface or dissolved metal sulfide traces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, moderate pH; proposed as a bottleneck reduction step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of the gamma-carboxyl functionality of glutamate generates the corresponding semialdehyde while retaining the alpha-amino acid backbone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The canonical precursor logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline is explicitly discussed as the relevant nonenzymatic route to proline precursors, but the semialdehyde-forming reduction has not been directly established under fully prebiotic conditions and remains the principal bottleneck. This reaction is therefore included as necessary but explicitly speculative (Somorjai et al., 2023; Kaur et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"spontaneous intramolecular cyclization in anoxic aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amino group intramolecularly attacks the aldehyde to form a five-membered cyclic imine/carboxylate system, yielding P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This spontaneous cyclization is the least controversial step in the glutamate-derived route and is specifically consistent with the literature summary that glutamate semialdehyde spontaneously cyclizes to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate in the canonical pathway (Somorjai et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"available reductants or metal-rich interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic reducing pool or mineral interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C gives pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The final reduction of P5C to proline is chemically consistent with the canonical route summarized in the literature, but no dedicated prebiotic experiment isolates this exact step under early Earth conditions. It is therefore plausible but incompletely demonstrated, and is included to complete the literature-identified precursor sequence (Somorjai et al., 2023; Kaur et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge formation of HCN-rich product mixture from methane, nitrogen, ammonia, and water\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"about 298K bulk flask\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge with mineral aerosols/surfaces as concentrative agents\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"high-energy spark, about 7000 V, CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electric discharge generates radicals from reduced atmospheric gases, leading to cyanide and related reactive carbon-nitrogen intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ring et al. (1972) showed Miller-type discharge chemistry in CH4/N2/H2O/NH3 systems produces amino acids including proline and is well known to generate HCN-rich product pools. Mineral agents are included here to satisfy the required surface-mineral schema and as plausible environmental concentrators, but the primary driver is the electric discharge rather than the minerals themselves (Ring et al., 1972).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge synthesis of proline from reduced atmospheric mixture\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"about 298K bulk flask\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge with mineral surfaces present in depositional setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"high-energy spark, about 7000 V, anoxic methane-nitrogen-ammonia-water atmosphere; proline detected as trace mixed-product amino acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex plasma radical chemistry generates multicarbon nitrogenous intermediates that hydrolyze and cyclize within the mixed product network to yield trace proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest direct abiotic route in the literature: Ring et al. (1972) qualitatively identified proline among amino acids formed in spark-discharge experiments. The detailed mechanistic sequence remains unresolved, but the empirical observation of direct proline formation is robust within mixed discharge chemistry (Ring et al., 1972).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydrolysis to formamide under UV-exposed surface conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photocatalysis on TiO2 and sulfide-rich surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV flux, anoxic, evaporitic or geothermal surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemically activated nitrile hydration/hydrolysis converts HCN-derived carbon-nitrogen species to formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary identifies UV photochemistry of HCN/H2O leading to formamide as part of plausible prebiotic surface chemistry and emphasizes nitrile-rich routes in mixed systems. While not specific to proline, this step provides a literature-consistent connector into broader UV-driven nitrogen chemistry (Simionato et al., 2018; Ring et al., 1972).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-ice radical formation of butylamine-like precursor from HCN/formamide-rich chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<100K to 300K depending transfer from ice analog to surface deposition\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm equivalent after delivery\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation and radical recombination on mineral-bearing ice/dust analog surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"radical-rich photochemical environment; route is transfer from astrochemical ice analog chemistry to planetary surface inventory\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of simple nitrogenous carbon-bearing ices produces radical fragments and reduced amines, including butylamine-like species implicated as proline precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. (2018) discuss UV-irradiated interstellar ice chemistry yielding proline and specifically note proposed radical-radical routes involving precursors such as butylamine. The exact conversion from HCN/formamide pools to butylamine is not experimentally isolated in the report and is therefore an explicitly speculative connector included only because the literature identifies butylamine-like precursors as relevant (Simionato et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-radical conversion of butylamine-like precursor to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<100K to 300K depending ice analog and subsequent planetary deposition\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low to 1 atm equivalent after transfer\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation with radical recombination on mineral-containing surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"interstellar/cometary ice analog radical chemistry; delivered organics incorporated into surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Radical-radical processing of butylamine-containing organic matrices leads to cyclic amino-acid products including proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. (2018) specifically note a proposed mechanism in UV-photolyzed interstellar ices where butylamine-related radicals can account for proline formation. This is literature-based but mechanistically underconstrained, so it is retained as a supported but low-definition route rather than a high-confidence dedicated synthesis (Simionato et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteoritic delivery of proline to the surface organic inventory\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"pyrite-like meteoritic metal sulfides\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm after deposition\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none intrinsic; mineral surfaces preserve and concentrate delivered organics\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"carbonaceous meteorite infall followed by dissolution in ponds or pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Exogenous proline synthesized in parent-body or interstellar chemistry is delivered to early Earth and enters local aqueous/mineral inventories.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Simionato et al. (2018) documented proline in carbonaceous meteorites such as Murchison and Murray, demonstrating a nonbiological source of preformed proline. This is not endogenous synthesis but is a literature-supported route supplying the target precursor pool to surface environments (Simionato et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral sorption and prebiotic pool integration of proline as environmental L-proline target pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite-rich interfaces and wet-dry concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pools, mineral interfaces, repeated cycling; no claim of abiotic enantioselective synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Proline produced or delivered by multiple pathways is concentrated, retained, and made available in protocell-relevant pools where the biologically relevant L-proline target inventory is defined operationally.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature does not demonstrate an abiotic enantioselective route to L-proline; products are generally racemic or stereochemically unspecified. This node therefore represents the biologically relevant L-proline target as part of the environmental proline inventory rather than a claimed chiral-resolution reaction. Mineral sorption and retention are supported by Cueto-Diaz et al. (2023), who showed proline adsorption on montmorillonite and Fe-sulfide surfaces, while wet-dry concentration and downstream peptide relevance are supported by Guo et al. (2024). This step is an inventory/availability mapping required by the target specification and explicitly not a claim of demonstrated prebiotic asymmetric synthesis (Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023; Guo et al., 2024).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal glutamate-P5C route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolic production of alpha-ketoglutarate followed by reductive amination, semialdehyde formation, cyclization, reduction to proline, and biochemical pool integration.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate to target via glutamate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortened view of the literature-centered alpha-ketoglutarate branch entering directly at the ketoacid hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate semialdehyde cyclization route\",\n      \"description\": \"Entry at glutamate formed in hydrothermal amino-acid chemistry, emphasizing the unresolved reduction bottleneck and subsequent spontaneous ring closure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"P5C reduction route\",\n      \"description\": \"Minimal completion route from the cyclic imine intermediate to proline and then to the target pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct trace proline formation in Miller-Urey-type atmospheric discharge experiments followed by biochemical availability.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge HCN-assisted mixed chemistry route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced atmospheric discharge first generates an HCN-rich product pool that converges with broader nitrile chemistry before proline availability is realized through the direct discharge product stream.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN to formamide to butylamine-like UV route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface nitrile chemistry passes through formamide and a butylamine-like precursor proposed in astrochemical studies before yielding proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-assisted UV-radical proline route\",\n      \"description\": \"A variant emphasizing HCN hydrolysis to formamide and subsequent radical processing to proline-bearing organic mixtures.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Butylamine-centered astrochemical delivery route\",\n      \"description\": \"Butylamine-like precursors generated in UV-processed ice analog chemistry undergo radical transformation to proline before entering surface and biochemical pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteoritic delivery route\",\n      \"description\": \"Exogenous proline from carbonaceous meteorites is delivered to early Earth and retained in prebiotic mineral-rich pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network uses the literature-supported reality that dedicated prebiotic L-proline synthesis is not established and that direct abiotic evidence is strongest from mixed-product spark-discharge, UV-irradiated ice chemistry, and meteoritic delivery, while the most chemically structured downstream route proceeds through the canonical alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate -> proline sequence. Because the literature does not justify an abiotic enantioselective synthesis of L-proline, the target is represented as environmental L-proline within a racemic/near-racemic proline pool, with pathways converging on proline-generating chemistry and subsequent incorporation into prebiotic biochemical settings. The network therefore emphasizes literature-backed precursor generation, mixed-chemistry direct formation, mineral-mediated concentration, and a speculative but explicitly labeled nonenzymatic glutamate/P5C branch needed to connect hydrothermal and surface chemistry to the target pool.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxo-2,3,4,5-tetrahydro-1H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(6-4)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9N", "iupac_name": "butan-1-amine", "common_name": "butylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H11N/c1-2-3-4-5/h2-5H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of alpha-ketoglutarate from CO2/H2 protometabolic chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-395K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite, Ni-bearing vent minerals as analog support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions; H2-rich, anoxic, pH about 8-11; alpha-ketoglutarate inferred within prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise CO2 reduction and carbon-skeleton building in an H2-driven protometabolic network over Fe-S/oxide mineral surfaces produces ketoacids including alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated an H2/NH4+-driven prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog over Ni-rich catalysts yielding biological ketoacid/amino-acid relationships, supporting alpha-ketoglutarate as a central prebiotic intermediate under mild aqueous conditions; hydrothermal Fe-S/mineral adaptation is consistent with vent geochemistry but exact vent-specific alpha-ketoglutarate generation remains partly inferential and therefore this connector is moderately speculative in environment transfer while retaining literature-consistent chemistry (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "moderate to high H2 availability", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing metal sites associated with Fe-S mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 8; NH4+ 6-150 mM equivalent; anoxic; adapted from Ni-catalyzed prebiotic amination experiments"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia followed by H2-driven reduction on metal/mineral catalytic sites gives glutamate.", "reasoning": "Directly grounded in the amino-acid-forming reductive amination chemistry reported by Kaur et al. (2024), who showed alpha-keto acids including alpha-ketoglutarate can be converted to their corresponding amino acids with H2 and NH4+ over nickel-rich catalysts at 22 C and pH 8. Use of Fe-S mineral surfaces here reflects the hydrothermal mineral context highlighted in the report and is chemically plausible, though the exact catalyst composition differs from the original Ni experiments (Kaur et al., 2024; Somorjai et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Nonenzymatic reduction of glutamate to glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": "reducing mineral interface or dissolved metal sulfide traces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, moderate pH; proposed as a bottleneck reduction step"}, "mechanism": "Partial reduction of the gamma-carboxyl functionality of glutamate generates the corresponding semialdehyde while retaining the alpha-amino acid backbone.", "reasoning": "The canonical precursor logic alpha-ketoglutarate -> glutamate -> glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde -> P5C -> proline is explicitly discussed as the relevant nonenzymatic route to proline precursors, but the semialdehyde-forming reduction has not been directly established under fully prebiotic conditions and remains the principal bottleneck. This reaction is therefore included as necessary but explicitly speculative (Somorjai et al., 2023; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-gamma-semialdehyde to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-373K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "none required", "aqueous": "true", "other": "spontaneous intramolecular cyclization in anoxic aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "The amino group intramolecularly attacks the aldehyde to form a five-membered cyclic imine/carboxylate system, yielding P5C.", "reasoning": "This spontaneous cyclization is the least controversial step in the glutamate-derived route and is specifically consistent with the literature summary that glutamate semialdehyde spontaneously cyclizes to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate in the canonical pathway (Somorjai et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reduction of Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": "available reductants or metal-rich interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic reducing pool or mineral interface"}, "mechanism": "Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C gives pyrrolidine-2-carboxylate.", "reasoning": "The final reduction of P5C to proline is chemically consistent with the canonical route summarized in the literature, but no dedicated prebiotic experiment isolates this exact step under early Earth conditions. It is therefore plausible but incompletely demonstrated, and is included to complete the literature-identified precursor sequence (Somorjai et al., 2023; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Spark-discharge formation of HCN-rich product mixture from methane, nitrogen, ammonia, and water", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "about 298K bulk flask", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electric discharge with mineral aerosols/surfaces as concentrative agents", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high-energy spark, about 7000 V, CH4/N2/H2O with traces of NH3, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Electric discharge generates radicals from reduced atmospheric gases, leading to cyanide and related reactive carbon-nitrogen intermediates.", "reasoning": "Ring et al. (1972) showed Miller-type discharge chemistry in CH4/N2/H2O/NH3 systems produces amino acids including proline and is well known to generate HCN-rich product pools. Mineral agents are included here to satisfy the required surface-mineral schema and as plausible environmental concentrators, but the primary driver is the electric discharge rather than the minerals themselves (Ring et al., 1972)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Direct spark-discharge synthesis of proline from reduced atmospheric mixture", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "about 298K bulk flask", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electric discharge with mineral surfaces present in depositional setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high-energy spark, about 7000 V, anoxic methane-nitrogen-ammonia-water atmosphere; proline detected as trace mixed-product amino acid"}, "mechanism": "Complex plasma radical chemistry generates multicarbon nitrogenous intermediates that hydrolyze and cyclize within the mixed product network to yield trace proline.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct abiotic route in the literature: Ring et al. (1972) qualitatively identified proline among amino acids formed in spark-discharge experiments. The detailed mechanistic sequence remains unresolved, but the empirical observation of direct proline formation is robust within mixed discharge chemistry (Ring et al., 1972)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "HCN hydrolysis to formamide under UV-exposed surface conditions", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photocatalysis on TiO2 and sulfide-rich surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV flux, anoxic, evaporitic or geothermal surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Photochemically activated nitrile hydration/hydrolysis converts HCN-derived carbon-nitrogen species to formamide.", "reasoning": "The literature summary identifies UV photochemistry of HCN/H2O leading to formamide as part of plausible prebiotic surface chemistry and emphasizes nitrile-rich routes in mixed systems. While not specific to proline, this step provides a literature-consistent connector into broader UV-driven nitrogen chemistry (Simionato et al., 2018; Ring et al., 1972)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "UV-ice radical formation of butylamine-like precursor from HCN/formamide-rich chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_014", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "<100K to 300K depending transfer from ice analog to surface deposition", "pressure": "low to 1 atm equivalent after delivery", "catalyst": "UV irradiation and radical recombination on mineral-bearing ice/dust analog surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "radical-rich photochemical environment; route is transfer from astrochemical ice analog chemistry to planetary surface inventory"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of simple nitrogenous carbon-bearing ices produces radical fragments and reduced amines, including butylamine-like species implicated as proline precursors.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. (2018) discuss UV-irradiated interstellar ice chemistry yielding proline and specifically note proposed radical-radical routes involving precursors such as butylamine. The exact conversion from HCN/formamide pools to butylamine is not experimentally isolated in the report and is therefore an explicitly speculative connector included only because the literature identifies butylamine-like precursors as relevant (Simionato et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "UV-radical conversion of butylamine-like precursor to proline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "<100K to 300K depending ice analog and subsequent planetary deposition", "pressure": "low to 1 atm equivalent after transfer", "catalyst": "UV irradiation with radical recombination on mineral-containing surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "interstellar/cometary ice analog radical chemistry; delivered organics incorporated into surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Radical-radical processing of butylamine-containing organic matrices leads to cyclic amino-acid products including proline.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. (2018) specifically note a proposed mechanism in UV-photolyzed interstellar ices where butylamine-related radicals can account for proline formation. This is literature-based but mechanistically underconstrained, so it is retained as a supported but low-definition route rather than a high-confidence dedicated synthesis (Simionato et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Meteoritic delivery of proline to the surface organic inventory", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "pyrite-like meteoritic metal sulfides"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "1 atm after deposition", "catalyst": "none intrinsic; mineral surfaces preserve and concentrate delivered organics", "aqueous": "true", "other": "carbonaceous meteorite infall followed by dissolution in ponds or pools"}, "mechanism": "Exogenous proline synthesized in parent-body or interstellar chemistry is delivered to early Earth and enters local aqueous/mineral inventories.", "reasoning": "Simionato et al. (2018) documented proline in carbonaceous meteorites such as Murchison and Murray, demonstrating a nonbiological source of preformed proline. This is not endogenous synthesis but is a literature-supported route supplying the target precursor pool to surface environments (Simionato et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Mineral sorption and prebiotic pool integration of proline as environmental L-proline target pool", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "montmorillonite-rich interfaces and wet-dry concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pools, mineral interfaces, repeated cycling; no claim of abiotic enantioselective synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Proline produced or delivered by multiple pathways is concentrated, retained, and made available in protocell-relevant pools where the biologically relevant L-proline target inventory is defined operationally.", "reasoning": "The literature does not demonstrate an abiotic enantioselective route to L-proline; products are generally racemic or stereochemically unspecified. This node therefore represents the biologically relevant L-proline target as part of the environmental proline inventory rather than a claimed chiral-resolution reaction. Mineral sorption and retention are supported by Cueto-Diaz et al. (2023), who showed proline adsorption on montmorillonite and Fe-sulfide surfaces, while wet-dry concentration and downstream peptide relevance are supported by Guo et al. (2024). This step is an inventory/availability mapping required by the target specification and explicitly not a claim of demonstrated prebiotic asymmetric synthesis (Cueto-Diaz et al., 2023; Guo et al., 2024)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical hydrothermal glutamate-P5C route", "description": "Hydrothermal protometabolic production of alpha-ketoglutarate followed by reductive amination, semialdehyde formation, cyclization, reduction to proline, and biochemical pool integration.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Alpha-ketoglutarate to target via glutamate branch", "description": "Shortened view of the literature-centered alpha-ketoglutarate branch entering directly at the ketoacid hub.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Glutamate semialdehyde cyclization route", "description": "Entry at glutamate formed in hydrothermal amino-acid chemistry, emphasizing the unresolved reduction bottleneck and subsequent spontaneous ring closure.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"